    (1) Recode the âvoteâ column: if the value is 1, recode it as 1; if the value is 2, recode it as 0; if the value is 3, recode it as NA. Make sure to include a sanity check for the recoded data. (2.5%)

    #type of your code/command here.

36804 11432  3688   534 
    ess_polity <- ess_polity %>%
mutate(vote = case_when(
 vote == 1 ~ 1,
 vote == 2 ~ 0,
 vote == 3 ~ NA_integer_,
 TRUE ~ NA_integer_  # Handle other cases as NA
))

print("Recode Vote Values:")

    0     1  <NA> 
11432 36804  4222

    The count of âNAâ values remains unchanged after the recoding process, confirming the validity of our sanity check.

  2. Suppose we want to test two hypotheses on the relationships of two pairs of variables. Please use the appropriate type of graphs we learned to visualize these two pairs of variables. Briefly describe the graph you plot, and answer: Does the graph we create from the data support the hypothesis?

    (1) Hypothesis#1: The more years of education (edu) a person completed, the higher income (income_10) they earn. (7.5%)

    # Scatter plot for Edu vs. Income_10
ess_polity|>
subset(!is.na(income_10))|>
subset(!is.na(edu))|>
ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(income_10), fill = as.factor(edu))) + 
geom_bar( position="fill", alpha = 0.8) +
labs(title = "Education Level vs. Income", x = "Income", y = "Count") +
scale_fill_discrete(name = "Education")

    The graph illustrating hypothesis 1 utilizes a stacked percentage bar chart to analyze the correlation between education level and income, displaying their aggregate values. This visualization method enables the observation of potential patterns or trends in these variables. Notably, it shows an increase in the proportion of individuals with the highest education level (4) within higher income groups. Therefore, based on the graph, our hypothesis appears to be valid.

    (2) Hypothesis#2: There is a gender disparity (male) in voting behavior (vote). (Either men are more likely to vote, or women are more likely to vote). (7.5%)

    #type of your code/command here.
ess_polity|>
subset(!is.na(male))|>
subset(!is.na(vote))|> 
ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(male), fill = as.factor(vote))) +
geom_bar(position = "fill") +
labs(title = "Gender Disparity in Voting Behavior", x = "Gender", y = "Count") + 
scale_x_discrete(labels = c("Female", "Male")) + 
scale_fill_discrete(name = "Vote", labels = c("Did not vote", "Voted"))

    ess_polity|>
group_by(male)|>
subset(!is.na(male))|>
subset(!is.na(vote))|>
summarise(mean(vote))

    Therefore, by using group_by and summarise(), we got that 76.7% of female and 75.9% of male have voted.Hence, our hypothesis is true in this case as we see a drastic difference in voting behaviour between men and women.

  2. Use a barplot to graph the Australian data based on their responses: yes, no, illegible, and no response. The y-axis should be the count of responses, and each response should be represented by one individual bar (so there should be four bars). (7.5%)

    (you can use either geom_bar() or geom_col())

    tidy_australian_data <- australian_data %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -c(X, District, Division), names_to = "Response", values_to = "Count")

head(tidy_australian_data, 5)
    tidy_australian_data_count <- tidy_australian_data %>%
  group_by(Response) %>%
  summarize(Count = sum(Count, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(tidy_australian_data_count, aes(x = Response, y = Count, fill = Response)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Australian Data Based on Responses", x = "Response", y = "Count of Responses") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1")

  3. The previous graph only shows the difference in amount. Letâs create a stacked-to-100% barplot to show the proportion of each of the four responses (by % of the total response). (7.5%)

    (you can use either geom_bar() or geom_col())

    prop <- data.frame(Response = tidy_australian_data_count$Response, Count = tidy_australian_data_count$Count)

tidy_australian_data_prop <- tidyr::gather(prop, key="Response", value="Count") %>%
                        transform(prop, Proportion = Count / sum(Count))

ggplot(tidy_australian_data_prop, aes(x=Response, y=Proportion, fill=Response)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  labs(title="Proportion of Responses",
   x="Response",
   y="Proportion") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent_format()) +
  theme_minimal()

  4. Letâs see if thereâs a relationship between Division and Response - that is, are certain divisions more likely to respond one way compared to other divisions? Again, we will use barplot(s) to present the visualization. (12.5%)

    (you can use either geom_bar() or geom_col())

    #type of your code/command here.
ggplot(tidy_australian_data, aes(x = Division, y = Count, fill = Response)) +

  2. Choose a pair of variables that may be correlated and make a graph (scatter plot or barplot) using them. Based on the visual evidence, do you see any potential correlation between the two variables (10%)

    #type of your code/command here.
summary <- aggregate(G3 ~ health, data=student_data, FUN=mean)

ggplot(summary, aes(x = health, y = G3)) +
geom_point(color = "orange") +
labs(title = "Scatter Plot of Student Health and G3 Grade", x = "Student Health", y = "G3 Grade") +
theme_minimal()

The better is studentâs health (health), the higher overall grade (G3) they achieve.

Relation: The relationship observed in the aggregate scatter plot between overall grade (G3) and student health suggests a quadratic association. Specifically, when health is at its poorest, students tend to achieve the highest grades. As health improves to a normal level, overall grades decline, but they rise again as health reaches a very good level. This indicates that our initial hypothesis, assuming a linear relationship, is not entirely accurate. Further statistical tests are necessary to draw precise conclusions.

Appendix: sources for data to be used in Part 3

Here are some online sources and popular Online Dataset Hub:

  1. Many US governments (usually at the federal and state levels),Â  bureaus, and departments have open data archives on their websites, allowing the public to access, download, and use them. Just use Google to search for them.

  2. The Harvard Dataverse Repository is a free data repository open to all researchers from any discipline, inside and outside the Harvard community, where you can share, archive, cite, access, and explore research data. Each individual Dataverse collection is a customizable collection of datasets (or a virtual repository) for organizing, managing, and showcasing datasets.

  3. Inter-university Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR) of the University of Michigan-Ann Arbor provides leadership and training in data access, curation, and methods of analysis for the social science research community.Â 

  4. UN: https://data.un.org/

  5. OECD Data:Â  economic and development data of the most developed countries in the world.

  6. The five sources above are mainly for social science data; there exists another very big community and open data archives for machine-learning and data science: Kaggle.
